help

The help command is a built-in command in Linux that is used to display information about built-in shell commands. It provides a quick reference for the syntax and usage of common shell commands.

The basic syntax of the help command is as follows:

scss
Copy code
help [command_name]
Here's what each part of the syntax means:

help is the command name.
[command_name] is an optional argument that specifies the name of the command you want help for.
Here are some examples of how to use help:

Display help for the cd command:

bash
Copy code
help cd
Display help for the ls command:

bash
Copy code
help ls
Display help for the help command:

bash
Copy code
help help
Note that help is only available for built-in shell commands, and not for commands that are installed as separate programs on the system. For those commands, you can typically refer to their manual pages using the man command.

For more information on how to use help, you can refer to the manual by typing help help in the terminal.
